# CI/CD Concepts

## Continuous Integration (CI)
Developers regularly merge code into a shared repository.

### Main Goals:
- Detect bugs early
- Improve code quality
- Avoid merge conflicts

---

## Continuous Deployment/Delivery (CD)
Automates software deployment after testing.

### Benefits:
- Faster releases
- Safer deployments
- Reduced manual work

---

# Deployment Workflow

Typical Workflow:

Developer → GitHub Commit → Testing → Validation → Deployment → Production

Each stage helps ensure software quality and stability.

---

# Why Production Editing is Dangerous

Direct production changes can:
- Break workflows
- Cause downtime
- Affect thousands of users
- Create security issues
- Corrupt data

Large systems require safe deployment processes.

---

# Importance of GitHub

GitHub provides:
- Version control
- Collaboration tools
- Branch management
- Change tracking
- Backup history

Without GitHub:
- Developers overwrite code
- No rollback support
- Difficult debugging

---

# Branching Concept

Branches allow developers to:
- Work independently
- Test safely
- Prevent unstable code from reaching production

---

# DevOps Thinking

DevOps combines:
- Development
- Testing
- Deployment
- Automation
- Monitoring

Goal:
Deliver software faster and more reliably.

---

# Enterprise Software Engineering

Enterprise systems require:
- Scalability
- Security
- Testing
- CI/CD pipelines
- Team coordination
- Release management

This is different from small personal projects.

---

# Rollback

Rollback means restoring a previous stable version when deployment fails.

Importance:
- Reduces downtime
- Protects users
- Maintains system stability

